content: Honestly a great game. I downloaded this a few days ago and have been obsessed with it since. Great controls and gameplay thats enjoyable, yet extremely challenging. Its so satisfying making a plan at the very start of a mission just to have it fail immidietly. That sounds weird but if it fails, it means you get to spend time perfecting it which is the most fun part. Door kickers is a great game, i couldn't recommend it more. Infact, i just wish the other games in the series was on the playstore

I've changed my review. This is a fine game after all. It simply lacks on the "pick up and play" front. The reason I changed my review is because the game needs a considerable investment of time to really master it, but once you do, it's well worth it. I love this game and have sunk a massive amount of time into it. That said there are a few mechanics that make the game absolutely infuriating. Specifically: 1. Teammates will turn a corner and enter a room before pointman has even thrown the flashbang/grenade. 2. Having to plan routes for every single team member really takes a lot of fun out of the planning phase in the big levels (which could be fixed by letting the player group team members and having them all follow the same instructions)

Controls need to be refined for mobile. In general, the concept is great and reminds me of the classic windows Swat game that was top down. But most the game is spent in the planning phase and that is where the most difficulty lies. The drag to move is decent but there's no undo button for if you make a mistake. I spent a few minutes seeing up a route with like 15 different moves, but thinking late and having to edit move 2 and that erased all the rest of my previous planning. Pretty annoying.

This is a very tactical and fun game which can be played on either your mobile phone or PC.  You are in charge of a SWAT team of officers and tasked with 1. threat elimination, hostage rescue, bomb defusing missions, etc.  For each mission completed the experience of your officers increases, making them more efficient and unlock talent points for each class (pistol, rifle, shotgun). You also gain points towards locking up better weapons!  You are given the option of where to place your officers before breach and then draw the path you want them to follow, down to the detail of in what direction to look. When faced with a door there are multiple options as to how to enter (kick in the door, lock-pick, demolition charge) and if you want to use a flash bang, stinger grenade etc.  The only complaint I have with this game is that the paths for each individual officer is not locked when drawing paths. When playing this on a mobile phone I have on many occasions accidentally moved the path of the wrong officer, resulting in me having to do the whole path all over again with that officer.  I hope the developers can implement something to fix this as it is incredibly annoying.

Have you ever wondered what it's like to plan a tactical raid? Well that's essentially the core gameplay of the game. Plan the raid, then execute it. It's got to be the most interesting Strategy game I have ever, other than the first Homeworld game. So what is it really like? Is it fun? Should you download it? It's like an RTS with a totally non linear control system. Each mission begins with a planning mode, then the deployment. The planning mode is very in depth. First you choose which officers you want to use. There are several factors involved in this, as there are 5 classes to choose from, which you unlock as your squad level increases. You can outfit them with a wide array of weaponry and kit, which you also unlock with star points, the unlock currency which you accumulate by playing missions and leveling up your officers. There is also an ability tree in the form of a squad doctrine, which allows your troopers to preform better with the weaponry you have assigned to them. YOU CAN RESET AND CHANGE THE DOCTRINE BEFORE ANY MISSION, SO THAT IT WORKS WITH THE LOAD OUT OF YOUR SQUAD. If you have ever played a tactical shooter like Swat 4 or one of the earlier (i.e BETTER) Rainbow Six games you can imagine what kind of equipment is available to use. So once you've figured out what you want your team to use you move onto the next phase of planning. There are two ways you can do this. You can make a full plan for the raid and then execute it to see if your tactics are successful, or you can make a partial plan and then continue to make it up as you go, based on the development of the situation, which is made possible by being able to pause the game mid raid. I personally like to experiment with both. Depending on the scenario one may prove superior than the other. what you're wanting is an end result in which no troopers are killed and the raid is finished under the desired time. This will earn you a three star rating on that mission, which gives the officers on that mission a higher XP reward. The controls are... Interesting. You may have read that a full plan for an officer can be wiped by accident rather easily, while this is true it becomes much less of a risk with practice. I play on my RAZER phone, which has a nice big screen but if you have a rather small screen on your phone I suggest getting the game on your tablet, if you own one. Either way it doesn't take long to master the controls. A good way to minimise the risk of scrubbing a plan by accident is to create waypoints often, there are strong tactical advantages to doing this other than insurance against your shaky hands or bumpy ride in the car. You can hold down your finger on any part of the individual officer path and orientate the direction the officer is facing, very useful for turning corners where bad guys are sure to be lurking, or for watching the backs of your team as they set up for a door entry. This also creates a way point, so if you make a mistake you can delete that part of the path safely without deleting the whole raid plan for that officer. Another way of doing this is to assign a go code, which is used primarily for synchronization but handily creates a waypoint. That's all I will say as I have said a whole lot already. Is it fun? Yes. Should you download it? Yes.

A very good tactical strategy game, with some amazing depth, and great gameplay. The controls on a phone are a bit tricky at times but the ability to zoom helps mitigate some of the issues. The preparation planning phase of the game is reminiscent of the pre-planning in the early SWAT and Rainbow 6 PC games, which is great, and the execution of perfectly planned assault is probably my personal highlight of the gameplay. Single missions range from short and simple tutorial levels and basic layouts, to long and complicated, multi-level scenarios. It should be noted, the adding of multi-story buildings is the clunkiest of mechanics in the game but was added at fervent community request, even though the game devs warned of the engine's in ability to handle exactly what the community requested. Honestly, this is all overlooked by the awesome campaign mode, custom random mission generator, and stellar squad customization and skills progression. Overall top notch mobile port of a great game, and a full recommendation!

While the game is fun to play, the controls seem designed for a mouse 
cursor. Even on my 5.7" phone, it is a bit difficult to accurately control 
the game. Allowing us to zoom in closer, alternate control of various units 
(so we don't accidentally move one person's path), and adjust earlier parts 
of the plan without affecting later parts would be really useful. Making 
the pause button in the top left bigger would also be nice.

The controls and general UI could be much better. For my display, the UI 
was small and sometimes hard to read. The controls are still difficult to 
learn because the video tutorials in the game are from the PC version while 
the UI doesn't show or hint to some of these controls. This is most 
prominent to the Alpha, Brovo, Charly keywords. I didn't know they existed 
until clicking on one of the units while planning the level. The other is 
the looking controls, have to hold my finger on the planning line for a 
moment before being able to control where the unit looks. Sometimes, in 
tight spots where lines overlap, I have to press multiple times to get the 
right unit looking in the set direction. I feel there definitely needs to 
be some work done for the UI and control direction. Other than that, the 
gameplay is really enjoyable and challenging.

squad name or a trooper's callsign, but overall this game is a lot of fun. 
Plenty of real world weapons and equipment to accrue, and mission 
challenges and flexible load-outs encourage experimentation to try and 
achieve the cleanest, fastest takedown. Play fully real-time or pause to 
plan and execute as needed. There are no wasted items, every gun has its 
situational uses and by upgrading your squad accordingly and leveling up 
the right stats (called Doctrines, representing firing drills and 
operational protocols specific to your squad) you can customize a 
devastating tactical police force to complement your personal play style.

I've been meaning to play this game for a while but finally picked it up about a month ago. Though the controls can sometimes be tricky and a bit frustrating (a way to lock in the directions given to a trooper so you can't accidentally delete them when trying to interact with other parts of the interface would be nice), the core gameplay is flawlessly designed. Successfully executing a mission based on a single, well-considered plan is incredibly satisfying. On top of that you have a slick interface, graphics polished to a shine, an awesome post-industrial soundtrack, a rewarding leveling system, tons of missions, plenty of variety in objectives, and mission achievements that encourage perfectionism. I wish the Android version allowed you to download user-generated maps, but I guess this is to account for the $16 price difference between the PC and Android versions. Otherwise, the Android version works great both as a pick-up-and-play timekiller and as a high-caliber strategy game-- strategy aficionados should well know how rare it is to find both in one package. Anytime I'm waiting for something, I whip out my phone and play a couple missions. This is overall a gem of a game, one of the Android's best strategy titles and more than worth its meager price tag. I'd recommend it to anybody who enjoys strategy games, has an interest in squad tactics, or just wants a fun and affordable timekiller.

Tl;dr the game is worth the small cost, does it have it's issues? Sure, but once you get used to the controls and if you love tactical realism games, you will never want to uninstall this.  This is the one mobile game i know i will never uninstall, it's fun to grind gear, the levels are unique, the game forces you to play tactically (if you wanna keep your full squad alive) and it's overall just a fun experience. The only issues i have with the game, however are 1) sometimes when trying to toss a flash through a door via the flash option, the flashband hits the corner of the door and lands back, ruining the flash and clear (and yes, the flashbang is not at an impossible angle to toss.) 2) a multitude of times have i had some complications with the line-dragging system to where I'll mess up the line and have to restart the pathway. For instance, say you have a squad go down a hallway and are stacked, there is no way to choose which line to choose from since the pathway lines are all on top of each other, and i've even had issues with picking individual units and end up messing up their pathway. 3) discloser: i totally understand that making graphics and artwork for a game is NOT easy, so this i will let slide since, again, the game is really a lot of fun. But i just feel that the character models are too... Cartoony. And that they just dont fit with the realistic design of the maps. If perhaps they were modified to where the animations werent as choppy and perhaps make the models look more realistic/ fit with the environment of the map, it would really make the game more surreal and really help with the simulation aspect.  Sorry for any typos for this was not reviewed at the time that i made this. this game will provide me with DAYS of gameplay and i look forward to if the game gets updated (especially if the isses above are looked into)

I wanted to like this game, I really REALLY wanted to like it. I just Can NOT.  Positives: Great Concept. Big Potential, Could be Lots of Fun & Addictive.  Negatives: The download for the game is 500mb. Then you have to download another 500mb, totalling out at 1gb+. I expected with a game that size, Expected the Graphics to be a lot better than the pics, they weren't as good as the pics. If the graphics & controls were close to being as good as other Top Down games such as Space Marshalls or Last Day on Earth, I would of Happy but the graphics are just not good. The controls are also a good concept need polishing. The game froze on me 2/3 of the 1st 3 times I played it, in the middle of the match. It continued to Freeze & Restart to the Main Menu, & it was Slow getting back there. The characters movements seem choppy & not fluid or smooth. The center button & the menu button for the characters needs to be Off Center so that we can see our character. Also I would like to see the entire character, head, legs, arms, his body like in the other Top Dwn games I named above. I feel like I'm moving 2 dots in between the lines. The buildings, houses, walls, everything the entire environment could be upgraded with a Graphics enhancement & an Artist. I dont know thr game isn't already their with it being 1gb+. That amazes me in its self. I imagine with some help from another developer that could be achieved. I don't think it ever will be, or why would it not already be that way?  Side Notes: Could be a Great Game, like a Top Game, Editors Choice. It's just not their & I doubt the developer will take the game in the direction they need to, to get it their. Good Luck, I'll check back in the future & see if it's gotten any better, like I said I really wanted to like it.

Back in the day, when the Rainbow Six series wasn't dumbed down, you had to carefully plan the actions of your entry team before each mission. This game is basically that. Planning the movement of your team and watching the events unfold is a very interesting experience, also extremely rewarding, if your plan works out flawlessly. The game can be challenging, but if you know a thing or two about real life tactics, you will have a lot of fun. Door Kickers is full of content. There are numerous scenarios, multiple campaigns, a mission generator, user created content and finally, mods. The game will keep you entertained for a long time, so it is well worth the asking price. I can wholeheartedly recommend this title to anyone who has an affinity for tactical games.
